sections:
  0. the-page-that-would-have-mattered [36mcinematic[0m/lg  Open with a concrete deploy-gone-wrong moment: a timeline showing a deploy, then an error spike, then the exact commit and person responsible, rendered as a real product screenshot rather than a claim.
  1. before-kettle    [36mnarrative[0m/md  Name the actual cost small teams pay today: a Slack thread of 'did anyone deploy?', a war room with no clear owner, minutes lost to guessing.
  2. what-changed-what-broke-who-to-ask [36mtimeline[0m/xl  Walk through the three-part product promise as a literal before/after workflow transition: commit lands, service health updates, owner is surfaced automatically.
  3. instrumentation  [36mmodular[0m/lg  Show the unequal-weight feature set: the hero capability is automatic root-cause correlation; secondary cells cover integrations, alerting, and audit history.
  4. how-a-team-actually-uses-it [36meditorial[0m/md  Give a short, specific engineering-team scenario (3-person startup, a Friday deploy, a broken payment webhook) to earn trust through plausibility rather than testimonial marketing.
  5. the-quiet-guarantee [36meditorial[0m/sm  Address trust and adoption friction directly: data retention, no-agent-on-prod-code claims, and what happens to your data if you cancel.
  6. free-for-three   [36masymmetric[0m/md  State the concrete pricing offer plainly: free up to 3 services, flat per-service pricing beyond that, one CTA to start monitoring.

